23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > TROUBLESHOOTING <A/T> > DIAGNOSIS TROUBLESHOOTING FLOW
DIAGNOSIS TROUBLESHOOTING FLOW
caution
  • After the trouble symptom diagnosis or part replacement/adjustment, always erase the set diagnosis code using the M.U.T.-III. Because the diagnosis code will not be erased even when the battery is removed, a misidentification may occur.
  • After replacing the transmission assembly or valve body assembly, always erase the shift change learning data stored in A/T-ECU, and reset all the stored data. Because the stored data is made compatible with the transmission assembly and valve body assembly before the replacement, it is not compatible with the new transmission assembly and valve body assembly after the replacement. After the A/T-ECU, transmission assembly or valve body assembly replacement, always perform the initial learning.
23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > TROUBLESHOOTING <A/T> > DIAGNOSIS FUNCTION
DIAGNOSIS FUNCTION
 
 
WARNING INDICATOR
If a malfunction relating to the A/T system occurs, the symbol (A) will be displayed on the information screen in the multi-information display.
Check if the diagnosis code is set when the symbol (A) continues being displayed in the information screen in the multi-information display.
noteOnly when the inhibitor switch is defective, symbol "A" will flash in the selector lever position indicator.
Symbol (B) (on the multi-information display) depends on the A/T fluid temperature, which A/T fluid temperature sensor informs of. When the symbol (B) is displayed in the information screen in the multi-information display, the A/T fluid temperature is high. (When the A/T fluid temperature sensor 1 detects the A/T fluid temperature of approximately 136°C or higher, symbol (B) is turned on. When it drops below approximately 131°C, symbol (B) is turned off automatically. Meanwhile, when the A/T fluid temperature sensor 2 detects the A/T fluid temperature of approximately 138°C or higher, symbol (B) is turned on. When it drops below approximately 128°C, symbol (B) is turned off automatically.)
noteWhen A/T fluid reaches a high temperature, the shift program for the "D" range will be modified to lower the A/T fluid temperature. It is control to lower temperature of A/T fluid, and this phenomenon is not trouble. If temperature of A/T fluid falls, A/T returns to normal movement.
 
 
 
METHOD OF READING THE DIAGNOSIS CODE
Use the M.U.T.-III to read the diagnosis code (Refer to GROUP 00 - How to Use Troubleshooting/Inspection Service Points ).
 
 
 
METHOD OF ERASING THE DIAGNOSIS CODE
Use the M.U.T.-III to erase the diagnosis code (Refer to GROUP 00 - How to Use Troubleshooting/Inspection Service Points ).

Emergency mode 2
Emergency mode 2 is the emergency mode activated when the functional failure is detected. Especially for clutch control solenoid (SL1) OFF stuck condition. Before moving the selector lever from the "D" position, 5th gear condition is kept. After moving the selector lever from the "D" position, and the vehicle speed for 3rd gear shifting is satisfied, all solenoids are turned off and the gear is ready to be shifted to 3rd when the selector lever is moved to "D" position. When the neutral condition is detected in the 3rd gear condition, the gear is shifted to 5th.

23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > TROUBLESHOOTING <A/T> > HOW TO INITIALISE A/T LEARNING VALUE
HOW TO INITIALISE A/T LEARNING VALUE
 
 
AIM
A/T learned value must be reset whenever the automatic transmission, engine assembly or valve body assembly is replaced. It cannot be reset by disconnecting the battery. Use the M.U.T.-III as follows:
 
 
 
INITIALISATION PROCEDURE
1. Move the selector lever to the "P" position and turn the ignition switch to the "LOCK" (OFF) position.
2. Connect the M.U.T.-III to the vehicle's diagnosis connector.
3. In the A/T/CVT/A-MT/TC-SST menu screen, select "Special Function," then select "Reset."
4. Select "OK" to reset the A/T learned memory.
noteA/T diagnosis codes and A/T freeze-frame data will be erased. (Engine diagnosis codes, engine-related freeze-frame data, and readiness status will remain even after A/T learned value is reset.)
 
 
23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > TROUBLESHOOTING <A/T> > A/T INITIAL LEARNING PROCEDURE
A/T INITIAL LEARNING PROCEDURE
caution
  • When the A/T or A/T-ECU is replaced, always initialise the learned value, and perform the initial learning.
  • Do not raise the A/T fluid temperature with engine stall.
  • If the A/T fluid temperature is not between 65 and 110°C, the initial learning cannot be performed.
1. Raise the A/T fluid temperature by leaving the vehicle at idle or performing a city driving. Subsequently, check the A/T fluid temperature data using the M.U.T.-III, and check that the A/T fluid temperature is at between 65 and 110°C.
noteAfter the A/T fluid temperature is raised, check the garage shift shock and shift shock status before the learning.
2. Make the A/T-ECU learn about the garage shift shock according to the procedure below:
(1) Depress the brake pedal with the vehicle stationary.
(2) Move and hold the selector lever to the "N" position for 3 seconds, and then move and hold it to the "D" position for 3 seconds.
(3) Repeat step (2) 5 times.
3. Make the A/T-ECU learn about the shift shock according to the procedure below:
(1) Accelerate the vehicle with the selector lever in "D" position until the speed reaches approximately 110 km/h and the 6th gear is engaged (throttle opening amount: approximately 25% to 35%).
(2) Subsequently, release the accelerator pedal to decelerate, and bring the vehicle to stop within 60 seconds.
(3) Repeat steps (1) and (2) 10 times.
4. Check that the garage shift shock and shift shock are alleviated compared to these before the learning.

The inhibitor switch detects the selector lever position ("P", "R", "N" or "D") which the driver has selected, and sends the information to the A/T-ECU.

Check Condition
  • Engine is running.
  • Vehicle speed is 30 km/h or more.
Judgement Criterion
  • Inhibitor switch position is not detected for 30 seconds or more.
 
 
PROBABLE CAUSES
  • Malfunction of the inhibitor switch
  • Damaged harness wires and connectors
  • Malfunction of the transmission control cable
  • Malfunction of the A/T-ECU
 
 
DIAGNOSIS PROCEDURE
STEP 1. Check the transmission control cable.
Check that the selector lever moves smoothly when shifting from "N" range to other range. Then check that the selector lever position indicator illuminates normally.
Is the check result normal?
Go to Step 2.
Adjust the transmission control cable (Refer to ).
 
STEP 2. Measure the resistance at the A/T-ECU connector.
(1) Disconnect the connector, and measure at the wiring harness side.
(2) Move the selector lever to the "P" position and check the resistance between A/T-ECU connector terminals INHP and IGSW.
OK: Continuity exists (2 Ω or less)
(3) Move the selector lever to the "R" position and check the resistance between A/T-ECU connector terminals INHR and IGSW.
OK: Continuity exists (2 Ω or less)
(4) Move the selector lever to the "N" position and check the resistance between A/T-ECU connector terminals INHN and IGSW.
OK: Continuity exists (2 Ω or less)
(5) Move the selector lever to the "D" position and check the resistance between A/T-ECU connector terminals INHD and IGSW.
OK: Continuity exists (2 Ω or less)
Is the check result normal?
Go to Step 7.
Go to Step 3.
 
STEP 3. Measure the voltage at the inhibitor switch connector.
(1) Disconnect the connector, and measure at the wiring harness side.
(2) Turn the ignition switch from the "LOCK" (OFF) position to the "ON" position.
(3) Check the voltage between the inhibitor switch connector (power supply terminal) and body earth.
OK: System voltage
Is the check result normal?
Go to Step 5.
Go to Step 4.
 
STEP 4. Check for short to earth and open circuit in power supply line between the ignition switch (IG1) or IG1 relay and the inhibitor switch connector.
Is the check result normal?
Intermittent malfunction (Refer to GROUP 00 - How to Cope with Intermittent Malfunction ).

Refer to .

Code No. P0711: A/T fluid temperature sensor 1 system (Malfunction)
 
 
 
 
OPERATION
  • The A/T fluid temperature sensor 1 converts the A/T fluid temperature to voltage, and send the information to the A/T-ECU.
  • The A/T fluid temperature rises, the resistance decreases. Thus, the sensor output voltage depends on the A/T fluid temperature. As the A/T fluid temperature rises, the output voltage will decrease.
 
 
DIAGNOSIS CODE SET CONDITIONS
Check Condition
  • Engine is running.
  • Vehicle speed is 40 km/h or more.
Judgement Criterion
  • A/T fluid temperature is lower than 20°C for 10 minutes or more.
 
 
PROBABLE CAUSES
  • Malfunction of the transmission wiring harness (A/T fluid temperature sensor 1)
  • Damaged harness wires and connectors
  • Malfunction of the A/T-ECU
 
 
DIAGNOSIS PROCEDURE
STEP 1. Measure the resistance at the A/T-ECU connector.
(1) Disconnect the connector, and measure at the wiring harness side.
(2) Check the resistance between A/T-ECU connector terminals O/TS and GRSE.
OK:
  • Approximately 6.5 kΩ (at 10°C)
  • Approximately 3.5 kΩ (at 25°C)
  • Approximately 0.25 kΩ (at 110°C)
(3) Check the resistance between the A/T-ECU connector terminal O/TS and body earth.
OK: No continuity
(4) Check the resistance between the A/T-ECU connector terminal GRSE and body earth.
OK: No continuity
Is the check result normal?
Go to Step 4.
Go to Step 2.
 
STEP 2. Check for harness damage between the A/T-ECU connector and the A/T control solenoid valve assembly connector.
Check the following lines between the A/T-ECU and the A/T control solenoid valve assembly connector.
  • O/TS
  • GRSE
Is the check result normal?
Go to Step 3.
Repair the connector(s) or the wiring harness.
 
STEP 3. Measure the resistance at the A/T control solenoid valve assembly connector.
(1) Disconnect the connector, and measure at the transmission wiring harness side.
(2) Check the resistance between the A/T control solenoid valve assembly connector terminals Nos. 8 and 7.
OK:
  • Approximately 6.5 kΩ (at 10°C)
  • Approximately 3.5 kΩ (at 25°C)
  • Approximately 0.25 kΩ (at 110°C)
(3) Check the resistance between the A/T control solenoid valve assembly connector terminals No. 8 and body earth.
OK: No continuity
(4) Check the resistance between the A/T control solenoid valve assembly connector terminals No. 7 and body earth.
OK: No continuity

23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > TROUBLESHOOTING <A/T> > DIAGNOSIS CODE PROCEDURES > CODE NO. P0828 SPORT MODE UP/DOWN SWITCH
Code No. P0828: Shift switch (up switch/down switch) system
 
 
 
 
OPERATION
The shift switch detects the up shift/down shift which the driver has selected, and sends the information to the A/T-ECU.
 
 
DIAGNOSIS CODE SET CONDITIONS
Check Condition
  • Ignition switch is in the "ON" position.
Judgement Criterion
  • UP/DOWN signal from shift switch is detected for 10 seconds or more while the select switch is not in the sport mode position.
 
 
PROBABLE CAUSES
  • Damaged harness wires and connectors
  • Malfunction of shift switch
  • Malfunction of the A/T-ECU
 
 
DIAGNOSIS PROCEDURE
STEP 1. Measure the voltage at the A/T-ECU connector.
(1) Disconnect the A/T-ECU connector, and measure at the wiring harness side.
(2) Turn the ignition switch to the "ON" position.
(3) Move the selector lever to the upshift position and hold the selector lever.
(4) Check the voltage between the A/T-ECU connector terminal UPSW and body earth.
OK: System voltage
(5) Move the selector lever to the position other than the upshift position and hold the selector lever.
(6) Check the voltage between the A/T-ECU connector terminal UPSW and body earth.

OPERATION
The A/T-ECU operates the electro-magnetic oil pump during idling stop to avoid the fluid pressure reduction.
 
 
DIAGNOSIS CODE SET CONDITIONS
When the gear engagement detection condition is met, the diagnosis code No. 277C is set.
Check Condition <Engine flare detection during auto start>
  • Engine is running.
  • Vehicle is driven with the selector lever in the "D" position.
  • Output shaft speed is less than 200 r/min.
  • Input shaft speed sensor is normal.
  • Output shaft speed sensor is normal.
  • Electro-magnetic oil pump system is normal.
Judgement Criterion <Engine flare detection during auto start>
  • The difference between the input shaft speed and output shaft speed, which is multiplied by the 1st gear ratio, is more than 350 r/min.
Check Condition <Gear engagement detection>
  • After the engine flare detection during auto start
  • Input shaft speed sensor is normal.
  • Output shaft speed sensor is normal.
  • Output shaft speed is less than 200 r/min.
  • Not during gear shifting

23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > TROUBLESHOOTING <A/T> > DIAGNOSIS CODE PROCEDURES > CODE No. P277D: EMOP Fluid Temperature High
Code No. P277D: Electro-magnetic oil pump system (High A/T fluid temperature) <Vehicles with AS&G system>
 
 
 
 
OPERATION
  • The A/T fluid temperature sensor 1 converts the A/T fluid temperature to voltage, and send the information to the A/T-ECU.
  • The A/T fluid temperature rises, the resistance decreases. Thus, the sensor output voltage depends on the A/T fluid temperature. As the A/T fluid temperature rises, the output voltage will decrease.
 
 
DIAGNOSIS CODE SET CONDITION
Check Condition
  • Ignition switch is in the "ON" position.
  • A/T fluid temperature sensor 1 is normal.
Judgement Criterion
  • A/T fluid temperature is 112°C or higher for 1 second or more.
 
 
PROBABLE CAUSES
  • High A/T fluid temperature
 
 
DIAGNOSIS PROCEDURE
STEP 1. Check whether the diagnosis code is set again.
(1) Leave the vehicle for a while with the engine idling until the A/T fluid becomes normal temperature.
noteYou can observe the A/T fluid temperature on M.U.T.-III data list item No. 7 (Refer to ).
(2) Check again if the diagnosis code No. P277D is set.
Is the diagnosis code No. P277D set?
Check the A/T fluid.
The diagnosis code was set to protect the electro-magnetic oil pump due to the high A/T fluid temperature, so this is not a malfunction.

23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > TROUBLESHOOTING <A/T> > SYMPTOM PROCEDURES > DRIVEAWAY FAULT (FORWARD DRIVING FAULT "D")
Inspection Procedure 2: Does not move forward
 
 
 
 
COMMENTS ON TROUBLE SYMPTOM
If the vehicle does not move forward when the selector lever is moved to the "D" position while the engine is idling, the cause is probably abnormal line pressure or a malfunction of the torque converter, valve body assembly or oil pump.
 
 
PROBABLE CAUSES
  • Insufficient A/T fluid amount, immixing of water or unspecified A/T fluid

COMMENTS ON TROUBLE SYMPTOM

noteAs the cause for the A/T fluid temperature warning lamp or A/T fluid temperature warning display on multi-information display to flash or not to go out, a combination meter malfunction and combination meter circuit malfunction are suspected.   • Malfunction of the A/T-ECU

To cancel this status, turn the ignition switch from the "LOCK" (OFF) to "ON" position.
Does the A/T fluid temperature warning lamp or A/T fluid temperature warning display on multi-information display illuminate or flash?
Go to Step 2.
The procedure is complete.

Using M.U.T.-III, perform CAN bus line diagnosis.
Is the check result normal?

Refer to .
Is the check result normal?
Go to Step 4.

STEP 4. Retest the system.
Is the trouble symptom reproduced?
Replace the A/T-ECU.
The procedure is complete.

23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > ON-VEHICLE SERVICE > ESSENTIAL SERVICE > A/T FLUID CHECK
A/T FLUID CHECK
 
 
FLUID LEAK CHECK
After cleaning the lower side of transmission, check visually or by touching that there is no oozing or leaking of fluid from the transmission.
 
 
 
FLUID LEVEL CHECK
cautionDuring the fluid level check, the A/T fluid temperature must be between 40 and 50°C. If the temperature is outside this range, set the A/T fluid temperature to the suitable temperature, and then check the fluid level.
 
 
<WHEN THE M.U.T.-III IS USED>
1. Connect the M.U.T.-III.
2. Pull the parking brake lever, and start the engine.
3. Depress the brake pedal, move the selector lever from the "P" to "D" position, and then move it to every position by holding 2 seconds or more at each position. Repeat this cycle twice, and then return the lever to the "P" position.
4. Using the M.U.T.-III, check that the A/T fluid temperature is between 40 to 50°C.
noteWhen the ambient temperature is low (10°C or lower), move the selector lever to the "P" position, warm up the engine for 15 minutes with the engine speed of 2,000 to 2,500 r/min. Then, the A/T fluid temperature becomes approximately 40°C. In such case, after the A/T fluid temperature increased, leave the engine idling for 5 minutes, and then check the fluid level.
5. Remove the filler plug and the overflow plug, and drain the fluid from the overflow plug hole.
6. <When the fluid is drained>
Wait until the fluid becomes oil drops, and then tighten the overflow plug with a new gasket and the filler plug with a new O-ring to the specified torque.
<When the fluid is not drained>
Pour in the fluid through the filler plug hole until the fluid is drained from the overflow plug hole. Wait until the fluid becomes oil drops, and then tighten the overflow plug with a new gasket and the filler plug with a new O-ring to the specified torque.
Tightening torque:
  • 20 ± 2 N·m (overflow plug)
  • 39 ± 15 N·m (filler plug)
 

 
 
<WHEN THE M.U.T.-III IS NOT USED>
1. Earth the diagnosis connector terminal No. 1.
2. Pull the parking brake lever, and start the engine.
3. Depress the brake pedal, move the selector lever from the "P" to "D" position, and then move it to every position by holding 2 seconds or more at each range. Repeat this cycle twice, and then return the lever to the "P" position.
4. Move the selector lever ("N" → "D" → "N") within 1.5 seconds, and continue the operation until the A/T fluid temperature warning lamp illuminates. After the A/T fluid temperature warning lamp illuminated, return the selector lever to the "P" position. The warning lamp goes out within a few seconds.
note
  • The status of A/T fluid temperature warning lamp shows if the A/T fluid temperature is suitable for the fluid level check.
    • Warning lamp is off: The A/T fluid temperature is 40°C or lower, thus checking is impossible.
    • Warning lamp is on: The A/T fluid temperature is between 40 to 50°C, thus checking is possible.
    • Warning lamp is blinking: The A/T fluid temperature is 50°C or higher, thus checking is impossible.
  • When the ambient temperature is low (10°C or lower), move the selector lever to the "P" position, warm up the engine for 15 minutes with the engine speed of 2,000 to 2,500 r/min. Then, the A/T fluid temperature becomes approximately 40°C. In such case, after the A/T fluid temperature increased, leave the engine idling for 5 minutes, and then check the fluid level.
5. Remove the filler plug and the overflow plug, and drain the fluid from the overflow plug hole.
6. <When the fluid is drained>
Wait until the fluid becomes oil drops, and then tighten the overflow plug with a new gasket and the filler plug with a new O-ring to the specified torque.
<When the fluid is not drained>
Fill the fluid from the filler plug until the fluid is drained from the overflow plug hole, and wait until the fluid becomes oil drops. Then, tighten the overflow plug with a new gasket and the filler plug with a new O-ring to the specified torque.
Tightening torque:
  • 20 ± 2 N·m (overflow plug)
  • 39 ± 15 N·m (filler plug)
 
 
 
23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > ON-VEHICLE SERVICE > ESSENTIAL SERVICE > A/T FLUID CHANGE
A/T FLUID CHANGE
If there is an A/T fluid changer, use it. If there is no A/T fluid changer, replace the fluid as described below.
noteIf you use an A/T fluid changer, disconnect the oil return hose from the oil return tube. Then connect the A/T fluid changer between them.
1.
cautionWhen draining the fluid from the drain plug hole, use a plate to prevent the fluid from dripping on the centre member assembly.
Remove the filler plug and the drain plug, and drain the fluid from the drain plug hole.
Discharge volume: Approximately 3.0 L
2. Install the drain plug with a new gasket in between, and tighten it to the specified torque.
Tightening torque: 20 ± 2 N·m
3. Remove the overflow plug.
4. Pour in the fluid through the filler plug hole until the fluid is drained from the overflow plug hole. Wait until the fluid becomes oil drops, and then tighten the overflow plug with a new gasket and the filler plug with a new O-ring to the specified torque.
Tightening torque:
  • 20 ± 2 N·m (overflow plug)
  • 39 ± 15 N·m (filler plug)
5. Check the fluid level (refer to ).
6. During the fluid level check, check the drained fluid for contamination. If the fluid is contaminated, perform steps 1 to 5 again.

INHIBITOR SWITCH AND CONTROL CABLE ADJUSTMENT
1. Remove the A/T case protector from the transmission case.
2. Move the selector lever to the "N" position.
3. Loosen the transmission control cable adjusting nut, and the inhibitor switch adjusting bolt.
4. Turn the inhibitor switch to adjust so that the "A" shown in the figure and the scribe line of inhibitor switch match.
5.
cautionBe careful not let the inhibitor switch slip out of place.
Tighten the adjusting bolt to the specified torque.
Tightening torque: 13 ± 2 N·m
6. Gently push the transmission control cable lever in the direction as shown, and tighten the adjusting nut to the specified torque.
Tightening torque: 23 ± 4 N·m
7. Check that the selector lever is at the "N" position.
8. Check that the transmission shifts to the correct position corresponding to the position of the selector lever, and that it functions correctly in that position.
9. Temporarily tighten each bolt shown in the illustration, then tighten the bolts to the specified torque in the order of A and B to install the A/T case protector to the transmission case.
Tightening torque:
  • 18 ± 3 N·m (A)
  • 11 ± 1 N·m (B)

INPUT SHAFT SPEED SENSOR CHECK
caution
  • Do not damage the input shaft speed sensor and its terminals.
1. Remove the bolt to remove the input shaft speed sensor from the transmission case.
2. Check that the continuity exists.
 
Measurement terminal No.Normal condition (check condition)
1 - 2Continuity exists (Less than 2 Ω)
noteWhen measuring the resistance, 100 kΩ or more may be detected. However, this is not due to a malfunction.
3. Connect the input shaft speed sensor connector and the battery as shown in the illustration.
4. Wave a steel material in front of the input shaft speed sensor tip (gap of 5 mm or closer) while measuring the current.
 
SignalNormal condition (check condition)
High12.0 - 16.0 mA
Low4.0 - 8.0 mA
5. Replace the input shaft speed sensor if there is no continuity or the measured current is not normal.
6. Apply A/T fluid to a new O-ring, and then install it onto the input shaft speed sensor.
7. Install the input shaft speed sensor to the transmission case with the bolt.
8. Tighten the input shaft speed sensor mounting bolt to the specified torque.
Tightening torque: 5.4 ± 1.5 N·m

3. If a solenoid fault is suspected, remove the valve body assembly to check.
 
 
 
CHECK AFTER VALVE BODY ASSEMBLY IS REMOVED
Remove the valve body assembly and inspect each solenoid installed on the valve body assembly by following the procedures below.

 
 
SL Solenoid Inspection
1.
caution
  • Do not remove the solenoid from the valve body assembly when measuring the resistance.
  • Do not damage the solenoid.
Use a multimeter to measure the resistance between the solenoid terminal and the solenoid body.
Standard value: 11 - 15 Ω (at 20°C)
2. Remove the solenoid.

3.
caution
  • Do not damage the solenoid.
  • Do not damage the solenoid terminal.
Connect the positive battery terminal to the solenoid terminal, and the negative terminal to the solenoid body, respectively. Then the solenoid should be activated.
4. When the solenoid is activated, air should flow through as shown in the figure.
5. Replace the valve body assembly if resistance or air flow is not normal.
 

 
 
Clutch Control Solenoid (S1, S2, S3, S4), Line Pressure Control Solenoid (SLT) and Lock-up Control Solenoid (SLU) Inspection
1.
caution
  • Do not remove the solenoid from the valve body assembly measuring the resistance.
  • Do not damage the solenoid.
Use a multimeter to measure the resistance between the solenoid terminals.
Standard value: 5.0 - 5.6 Ω (at 20°C)

2.
caution
  • Do not damage the solenoid.
  • Do not damage the solenoid terminal.
Connect a lamp bulb (12 V - 21 W) between the solenoid terminal No. 2 and the positive battery terminal.
3. Connect the solenoid terminal No. 1 to the negative battery terminal. Then the solenoid should be activated.
4. Replace the valve body assembly if the resistance is not normal or the solenoid is not activated.
 

 
 
Electro-magnetic Oil Pump (EMOP) <Vehicles with AS&G System>
1.
caution
  • Do not remove the electro-magnetic oil pump from the valve body assembly measuring the resistance.
  • Do not damage the electro-magnetic oil pump.
Use a multimeter to measure the resistance between the electro-magnetic oil pump terminals.
Standard value: 5.0 - 5.6 Ω (at 20°C)

2.
caution
  • Do not damage the electro-magnetic oil pump.
  • Do not damage the electro-magnetic oil pump terminal.
Connect a lamp bulb (12 V - 21 W) between the electro-magnetic oil pump terminal No. 1 and the positive battery terminal.
3. Connect the electro-magnetic oil pump terminal No. 2 to the negative battery terminal. Then the electro-magnetic oil pump should be activated.
4. Replace the valve body assembly if the resistance is not normal or the electro-magnetic oil pump is not activated.

23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > ON-VEHICLE SERVICE > TORQUE CONVERTER STALL CHECK
TORQUE CONVERTER STALL CHECK
 
 
This test measures the maximum engine speed at the time the torque converter stalls with the selector lever in the "D" or "R" position. With this test, the holding abilities of the clutch and brake that are incorporated in the transmission can be checked.
1.
warningFor safety, operators must not stand in front of and at the rear of the vehicle during this test.
Check the A/T fluid temperature.
  • A/T fluid temperature: 50 - 80°C
  • Switches for air conditioner, lamps, and others shall be OFF.
noteUse the M.U.T.-III to measure the A/T fluid temperature.
2. Raise the vehicle.
3. Pull the parking brake lever, and then fully depress the brake pedal.
4. Start the engine.
5.
caution
  • Do not maintain the throttle fully opened condition for 5 seconds or longer.
  • Perform the measurement for 3 times or more, and obtain the average value of the measurements.
  • When continuing the stall test, make sure that the A/T fluid temperature does not exceed 80°C. If the A/T fluid temperature exceeds 80°C, perform the test after running the engine at around 1,000 r/min for 1 minute or longer and then cooling the A/T fluid to 80°C or lower.
Move the selector lever to the "D" position and fully depress the accelerator pedal. Quickly read the maximum engine speed at this time.
Standard value: 2,647 ± 150 r/min
6. Move the selector lever to the "D" position, and then repeat the previous step.
Standard value: 2,647 ± 150 r/min
 
 
 
TORQUE CONVERTER STALL TEST JUDGEMENT
Stall test resultProbable cause
Both "D" and "R" position are less than the standard value.
  • Insufficient engine output
  • Malfunction of one-way clutch in torque converter
Only "D" position is higher than the standard value.
  • Line pressures is low (malfunction of the line pressure control solenoid SLT, malfunction of the primary regulator valve).
  • Malfunction of the valve body (SL1 oil pressure system)
  • Malfunction of the clutch No. 1 (C1) (slip)
  • Malfunction of the one-way clutch No. 3 (F3)
Only "R" position is higher than the standard value.
  • Line pressures is low (malfunction of the line pressure control solenoid SLT, malfunction of the primary regulator valve).
  • Malfunction of the valve body (SL4 oil pressure system)
  • Malfunction of the brake No. 1 (B1) (slip)
  • Malfunction of the brake No. 4 (B4) (slip)
Both "D" and "R" position are higher than the standard value.
  • Line pressures is low (malfunction of the line pressure control solenoid SLT, malfunction of the primary regulator valve).
  • Malfunction of the oil pump
  • Oil strainer clogged
 
 
23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > ON-VEHICLE SERVICE > TIME LAG TEST
TIME LAG TEST
 
 
The time lag test indicates the measurement of time until a shock is felt after a shift change is performed during idle from "N" position to "D" or "R" position. This test checks the statuses of clutch, brake, and hydraulic pressure.
1.
warningFor safety, operators must not stand in front of and at the rear of the vehicle during this test.
Check the A/T fluid temperature.
  • A/T fluid temperature: 50 - 80°C
  • Switches for air conditioner, lamps, and others shall be OFF.
noteUse the M.U.T.-III to measure the A/T fluid temperature.
2. Raise the vehicle.
3. Pull the parking brake lever, and then fully depress the brake pedal.
4. Start the engine.
5.
caution
  • Perform the measurement for 3 times or more, and obtain the average value of the measurements.
  • The interval of time lag test must be 1 minute or more. (To eliminate the residual pressure of clutches and brakes)
Measure the time starting from the moment a shifting is performed from "N" to "D" or "R" position until a shock is felt.
Standard value:
"N" to "D" position: 1.2 seconds or less
"N" to "R" position: 1.2 seconds or less
 
 
 
TIME LAG TEST JUDGEMENT
Time lag test resultProbable cause
Time lag at shifting from "N" to "D" position is longer than the standard value.
  • Malfunction of the valve body (SL1 oil pressure system)
  • Malfunction of the clutch No. 1 (C1) (slip)
  • Malfunction of the one-way clutch No. 3 (F3)
  • Malfunction of the oil pump
  • Oil strainer clogged
Time lag at shifting from "N" to "R" position is longer than the standard value.
  • Malfunction of the valve body (SL4 oil pressure system)
  • Malfunction of the brake No. 1 (B1) (slip)
  • Malfunction of the brake No. 4 (B4) (slip)
  • Malfunction of the oil pump
  • Oil strainer clogged
 
 
23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > ON-VEHICLE SERVICE > HYDRAULIC PRESSURE TESTS
HYDRAULIC PRESSURE TEST
 
 
This test measures the line pressure when the selector lever is in the "D" or "R" position with the engine idling or stalled. With this test, the operation status of the transmission components can be checked.
1.
warningFor safety, operators must not stand in front of and at the rear of the vehicle during this test.
Check the A/T fluid temperature.
  • A/T fluid temperature: 50 - 80°C
  • Switches for air conditioner, lamps, and others shall be OFF.
noteUse the M.U.T.-III to measure the A/T fluid temperature.
2. Raise the vehicle.
3. Remove the plug from the line pressure take off port, and install special tools as shown in the figure and place the meter inside vehicle.
  • Oil pressure gauge <3.0 MPa> (MD998330)
  • Adapter (MD998920)
4. Pull the parking brake lever, and then fully depress the brake pedal.
5. Start the engine.
6.
caution
  • Do not maintain the throttle fully opened condition for 5 seconds or longer.
  • Perform the measurement for 3 times or more, and obtain the average value of the measurements.
  • When successively performing the test under the stall state, only perform the test after checking that the A/T fluid temperature is not at 80°C or higher. If the A/T fluid temperature exceeds 80°C, perform the test after running the engine at around 1,000 r/min for 1 minute or longer and then cooling the A/T fluid to 80°C or lower.
7. Shift the selector lever to "D" and "R" position, and measure the idle state line pressure and stall state line pressure.
Standard value:
ItemLine pressure (MPa)
DR
Idling0.36 - 0.46
Stall1.58 - 1.75
 
 
 
HYDRAULIC PRESSURE TEST JUDGEMENT
Hydraulic pressure test resultProbable cause
Both "D" and "R" position are less than the standard value.
  • Malfunction of the line pressure control solenoid (SLT)
  • Malfunction of the primary regulator valve
  • Malfunction of the oil pump
  • Oile leak from "D" or "R" position oil pressure circuit
Both "D" and "R" position are higher than the standard value.
  • Malfunction of the line pressure control solenoid (SLT)
  • Malfunction of the primary regulator valve
Only "D" position is less than the standard value.
  • Malfunction of the "D" position oil pressre circuit
  • Malfunction of the clutch No. 1 (C1)
Only "D" position is higher than the standard value.
  • Malfunction of the line pressure control solenoid (SLT)
  • Malfunction of the brake No. 1 (B1)
  • Malfunction of the brake No. 4 (B4)
Only "R" position is less than the standard value.
  • Malfunction of the "R" position oil pressre circuit
Only "R" position is higher than the standard value.
  • Malfunction of the line pressure control solenoid (SLT)
  • Malfunction of the corresponding solenoid valve

23 -AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION > 23C-AUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION<R6AWH, V6AWH> > ON-VEHICLE SERVICE > SELECTOR LEVER OPERATION CHECK
SELECTOR LEVER OPERATION CHECK
1. Apply the parking brake, and check that the selector lever moves smoothly and accurately to each position.
2. Check that the engine starts when the selector lever is in the "N" or "P" position, and that it does not start when the selector lever is in any other position.
3. Start the engine, release the parking brake, and check that the vehicle moves forward when the selector lever is moved from "N" position to the "D" position, and that the vehicle reverses when the selector lever is moved to the "R" position.
4. Stop the engine.
5. Turn the ignition switch to "ON" position. Check that the backup lamp illuminates when the selector lever is moved from "P" position to "R" position.
noteThe shift lock mechanisms prevent movement of the selector lever from the "P" position if the ignition switch is in a position other than "LOCK" (OFF) and the brake pedal is not depressed.
